<p><strong>16. Saving Ceecee Honeycutt (Unabridged) by Beth Hoffman</strong><br /> <br />
  <img align="left" alt="Saving-ceecee-honeycutt-unabridged" hspace="5" src="http://www.castlibrary.com/audio-book-images/000/044/493/saving-ceecee-honeycutt-unabridged/small/saving-ceecee-honeycutt-unabridged.jpg?1296666170" />Summary:    Steel Magnolias  meets  The Help  in this Southern debut novel sparkling with humor, heart, and feminine wisdom.  Twelve-year-old CeeCee Honeycutt is in trouble. For years, she has been the caretaker of her psychotic mother, Camille-the tiara-toting, lipstick-smeared laughingstock of an entire town-a woman trapped in her long-ago moment of glory as the 1951 Vidalia Onion Queen. But when Camille is hit by a truck and killed, CeeCee is left to fend for herself. To the rescue comes her previou&#8230;<br /> <br />
Click to hear an audio sample of <a href="http://www.castlibrary.com/audio_books/saving-ceecee-honeycutt-unabridged/?t202kw=bestdp">Saving Ceecee Honeycutt (Unabridged) audiobook</a>&#8230;
</p>
<p><strong>17. The Hunger Games (Unabridged) by Suzanne Collins</strong><br /> <br />
  <img align="left" alt="Hunger-games-unabridged" hspace="5" src="http://www.castlibrary.com/audio-book-images/000/000/104/hunger-games-unabridged/small/hunger-games-unabridged.jpg?1296666170" />Summary:  Could you survive on your own, in the wild, with everyone out to make sure you don&#8217;t live to see the morning? In the ruins of a place once known as North America lies the nation of Panem, a shining Capitol surrounded by 12 outlying districts.  The Capitol is harsh and cruel and keeps the districts in line by forcing them all to send one boy and one girl between the ages of 12 and 18 to participate in the annual Hunger Games, a fight to the death on live TV. 16-year-old Katniss Everdeen, who l&#8230;<br /> <br />
Click to hear an audio sample of <a href="http://www.castlibrary.com/audio_books/hunger-games-unabridged/?t202kw=bestdp">The Hunger Games (Unabridged) audiobook</a>&#8230;
</p>
<p><strong>18. Skippy Dies by Paul Murray</strong><br /> <br />
  <img align="left" alt="Skippy-dies" hspace="5" src="http://www.castlibrary.com/audio-book-images/000/045/653/skippy-dies/small/skippy-dies.jpg?1296666171" />Summary:   This touching and uproarious novel by author Paul Murray made everyone&#8217;s best fiction of 2010 lists, including  The Washington Post ,  Financial Times ,  Village Voice , and others. Why Skippy dies and what happens next is the mystery that links the boys of Dublin&#8217;s Seabrook College (Ruprecht Van Doren, the overweight genius obsessed with string theory; Carl, the teenager drug dealer and borderline psychotic; Philip Kilfether, the basketball-playing midget) to their parents and teachers in w&#8230;<br /> <br />
